The [[Internal Revenue Service|IRS]], since 1992, has shadowed and recorded the top four hundred people who make the most [[gross income]], and they are call the Fortunate 400.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://taxfoundation.org/article/fortunate-400|title=The Fortunate 400|website=Tax Foundation|access-date=2016-04-19}}</ref>
== Summary == The Fortunate 400 are basically the richest people in the [[United States]]. In 1992, when the IRS starting tracking the people who make the most money, the 400th richest person in America made $24 million. Then In 2007, the 400th [[The World's Billionaires|richest human]] produced $138 million (or $87 million, inflation-adjusted).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2012/07/how-the-richest-400-people-in-america-got-so-rich/259520/|title=How the Richest 400 People in America Got So Rich|last=Thompson|first=Derek|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-19}}</ref> These riches have come from [[capital gain]], and the rich keep making more money.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2012/07/how-the-richest-400-people-in-america-got-so-rich/259520/|title=How the Richest 400 People in America Got So Rich|last=Thompson|first=Derek|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-19}}</ref> There is a constant question and debate in politics whether or not the rich need more tax cuts or need to pay more [[Taxation in the United States|taxes]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nationalmemo.com/david-cay-johnston-the-fortunate-400/|title=David Cay Johnston: The Fortunate 400 - The National Memo - Smart. Sharp. Funny. Fearless.|website=[[The National Memo]]|language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-19}}</ref>
