{{Infobox book | image = Plausible Worlds.jpg | name = Plausible Worlds | author = Geoffrey Hawthorn | country = United Kingdom | language = English | subject = [[Counterfactual history]] | publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]] | release_date = August, 1991 (hardcover) | media_type = Hardcover, Paperback | pages = 206 pages (hardcover) | isbn = 0-521-40359-6 | isbn_note = (hardcover) | dewey= 901 20 | congress= D16.9 .H39 1991 | oclc= 22664059 }}
'''''Plausible Worlds: Possibility and Understanding in History and the Social Sciences''''' is a 1991 book by [[Geoffrey Hawthorn]], professor of [[sociology]] at the [[University of Cambridge]]. The book is credited with legitimizing the academic field of [[counterfactual history]].<ref>{{citation | last=Smoler | first=Fredric | year=1999 | title=Past Tense | periodical=[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]] | volume=50 | issue=5 | url=http://www.americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/ah/1999/5/1999_5_45.shtml}}</ref>
The book explores three [[Point of divergence|points of divergence]]: the [[Black Death]], the [[Korean War]], and the influence of [[Duccio]].
