===Live-action film===
{{main|School-Live! (film)}}
A live-action film adaptation of ''School-Live!'' was announced in the January 2018 issue of ''Manga Time Kirara Forward'' in November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|date=November 21, 2017|accessdate=December 17, 2017|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|title=School-Live! Manga Gets Live-Action Film|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-11-21/school-live-manga-gets-live-action-film/.124338}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=November 23, 2017|accessdate=December 17, 2017|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|title=Live-Action School-Live! Film Is Slated for 2018|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2017-11-23/live-action-school-live-film-is-slated-for-2018/.124402}}</ref> The film is being directed by Issei Shibata and will star the members of idol group Last Idol,<ref>{{cite web|date=December 14, 2017|accessdate=December 17, 2017|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|title=Live-Action School-Live! Film Casts 'Last Idol' Group|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-12-14/live-action-school-live-film-casts-last-idol-group/.125263}}</ref> and is planned to be released in Japan in January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|date=September 20, 2018|accessdate=September 20, 2018|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|title=Live-Action School-Live! Film's Visual Reveals January Opening|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-09-20/live-action-school-live-film-visual-reveals-january-opening/.137039}}</ref>

===Appearances in other media===
Yuki appeared as a support character in a [[fighting game]] called ''[[Nitroplus Blasterz: Heroines Infinite Duel]]'', which was released in December 2015.<ref>{{cite web|date=August 19, 2015|accessdate=December 17, 2017|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|title=Nitroplus Blasters Heroines Infinite Duel Game Adds School-Live!'s Yuki|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-08-19/nitroplus-blasters-heroines-infinite-duel-game-adds-school-live-s-yuki/.91857}}</ref> Characters from the series appear alongside other ''Manga Time Kirara'' characters in the 2017 mobile RPG, ''[[Kirara Fantasia]]''.<ref>{{cite web|date=June 25, 2017|accessdate=December 17, 2017|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|title=Houbunsha Reveals Kirara Fantasia Smartphone RPG|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-06-25/houbunsha-reveals-kirara-fantasia-smartphone-rpg/.117972}}</ref>

==Reception==
The first episode of the anime was well-received and sparked a ten-fold increase in manga sales. It was also viewed more than 1&nbsp;million times on [[Niconico]].<ref>{{cite web|language=Japanese|date=July 18, 2015|accessdate=September 24, 2015|publisher=ほんのひきだし|title=アニメ化影響で『がっこうぐらし！』の売上前週比がなんと10倍！ニコニコ動画再生数100万超えの大ブレイク夏アニメ |url=http://hon-hikidashi.jp/enjoy/2968/}}</ref>

The official Twitter of Houbunsha's ''Manga Time Kirara'' magazines has announced that ''School-Live!'' has 2 million copies in print as of March 2017.<ref>{{cite web|date=February 22, 2017|accessdate=March 1, 2017|publisher=[[Crunchyroll]]|title="School-Live!" Manga to Have 2 Million Copies in Print Next Month|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2017/02/22/school-live-manga-to-have-2-million-copies-in-print-next-month}}</ref>  The English release of the first three volumes were also included on the [[American Library Association]]'s list of 2017 Great Graphic Novels for Teens,<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=March 1, 2017|publisher=[[American Library Association]]|title=2017 Great Graphic Novels for Teens |url=http://www.ala.org/yalsa/2017-great-graphic-novels-teens}}</ref> and the fifth and sixth volumes made the 2018 list.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=February 16, 2018|publisher=[[American Library Association]]|title=2018 Great Graphic Novels for Teens |url=http://www.ala.org/yalsa/2018-great-graphic-novels-teens}}</ref>

