{{Notability|Organizations|date=April 2012}} {{Coord|51.523563|-0.132517|display=title}} {{Infobox institute |name = UCL Centre for Digital Humanities |image = [[File:UCLDH logo.png]] |image_size = 150 x 135 |image_name = |image_alt = |caption = |established = 2010 |president = |chairman = |head_label = Director |head = Simon Mahony |faculty = |staff = |budget = |endowment = |debt = |members = |location = |city = [[London]] |state = |province = |country = [[United Kingdom]] |coor = |address = UCL Centre for Digital Humanities Department of Information Studies University College London Gower Street London WC1E 6BT |website = [http://www.ucl.ac.uk/dh/ UCL Centre for Digital Humanities] |footnotes = }}
The '''UCL Centre for Digital Humanities''' is a cross-faculty research centre of [[University College London]]. It brings together [[digital humanities]] work being done in many of the university's different departments and centres, including the library services, museums and collections.<ref name=itnow>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1093/itnow/bws019| issn = 1746-5702| volume = 54| issue = 1| pages = 50–51| last = Terras| first = Melissa| title = Understanding Jane| journal = IT Now}}{{Failed verification|date=May 2012}}</ref> The Centre counts among the "most visible"<ref name=caraco>{{Cite journal| volume = 57| issue = 2| last = Caraco| first = Benjamin| title = Les digital humanities et les bibliothèques | journal = Le [[Bulletin des bibliothèques de France|Bulletin des Bibliothèques de France]]| accessdate = 12 April 2012| date = 1 January 2012| url = http://bbf.enssib.fr/consulter/bbf-2012-02-0069-002#appelnote-11}}</ref> in the field and facilitates various opportunities for study at post-graduate level, including the [http://www.ucl.ac.uk/dh/courses/mamsc MA/MSc in Digital Humanities], [http://www.ucl.ac.uk/dh/courses/doctorates doctoral study], and [http://www.ucl.ac.uk/dh/courses/short short courses] as part of the [[UCL Department of Information Studies|Department of Information Studies]].<ref name=itnow /><ref name=caraco />
==History==
The Centre was opened on 1 February 2010, with a launch party on 20 May.<ref>{{Cite news| last = Andrews| first = Robert| title = James Murdoch Lecture: Celebrating Copyright's 300th Birthday| work = Paid Content| accessdate = 2010-08-16| date = 2010-05-20| url = http://paidcontent.co.uk/article/419-james-murdoch-lecture-celebrating-copyrights-300th-birthday/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| title = James Murdoch launches UCL's Centre for Digital Humanities| work = UCL News| accessdate = 2010-07-30| date = 2010-05-21| url = http://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/news-articles/1005/10052101}}</ref><ref name=guardwray>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/may/21/james-murdoch-attacks-british-library|title=James Murdoch attacks British Library for digitising newspapers|accessdate=31 October 2010|publisher=The Guardian|date=21 May 2010}}</ref> At the launch party the inaugural Centre for Digital Humanities Lecture was given by [[James Murdoch (media executive)|James Murdoch]], the [[Europe, the Middle East and Africa|EMEA]] [[Chief executive officer|Chief Executive Officer]] of [[News Corporation]].<ref name=guardwray/><ref name=lesblackhurst>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard-business/article-23845548-sky-is-not-the-limit-for-ambitions-of-james-murdoch.do|title=Sky is not the limit for ambitions of James Murdoch|accessdate=31 October 2010|publisher=London Evening Standard|date=16 June 2010}}</ref><ref name=newstates>{{cite news|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/newspapers/2010/05/library-digital-murdoch|title=James Murdoch criticises British Library's digital newspaper archive plan|accessdate=31 October 2010|publisher=New Statesman|date=21 May 2010}}</ref> The speech attracted considerable media coverage due to its criticism of the [[British Library|British Library's]] plans to digitise its national newspaper collection.<ref name=guardwray/><ref name=lesblackhurst/><ref name=newstates/>
The Centre was introduced to the Digital Humanities community at large by Melissa Terras in her keynote address at the [[Digital Humanities conference]] in London on July 10.<ref>{{Cite news| last = Cunnane| first = Sarah| title = As a discipline, we suck online| work = Times Higher Education| accessdate = 2010-07-29| date = 2010-07-15| url = http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=26&storycode=412549&c=1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| last = Welsh| first = Anne| title = UCLDH (and DH) in the news| work = DH Blog| accessdate = 2010-07-31| date = 2010-07-15| url = http://www.ucl.ac.uk/dh-blog/2010/07/15/ucldh-and-dh-in-the-news/}}</ref>
The Centre hosts the annual [[Susan Hockey]] [http://www.ucl.ac.uk/dh/events/SusanHockeyLecture lecture series], which was inaugurated in May 2015.<ref>https://www.ucl.ac.uk/dh/events/SusanHockeyLecture</ref>
==Research== A number of research projects at [[University College London|UCL]] are associated with UCLDH:<ref>{{Cite web| title = Projects| work = UCL Centre of Digital Humanities| accessdate = 2010-08-09| year = 2010| url = http://www.ucl.ac.uk/dh/projects}}</ref> * Archaeology of Reading in Early Modern Europe - this new digital humanities research initiative explores historical reading practices through the lens of manuscript annotations preserved in early printed books. * Assyrian Empire Builders and State Archives of Assyria Online - study the mechanisms of communication between the top levels of authority in an ancient empire. * CELM: Catalogue of English Literary Manuscripts - is preparing a free on-line record of surviving manuscript sources for over 200 major British authors of the period 1450-1700. * DHOER: Digital Humanities Open Educational Resources - is creating a range of introductory Digital Humanities teaching materials and making them freely available. * Digital Lives - focuses on personal digital archives and their relationship with research repositories. * eSAD: e-Science and Ancient Documents - aims to use computing technologies to aid experts in reading ancient documents. * Humanities Information Practices - studies the range of information behaviors in the humanities. * INKE: Implementing New Knowledge Environments - proposes to design new digital environments for reading and research in the humanities, and for the general public. * LinkSphere - is creating a single virtual interface for searching across the repositories and collections held by the [[University of Reading]]. * Livingstone Online provides access to the medical and scientific writings of the missionary, doctor and African explorer [[David Livingstone]] (1813–1873). * Open Learning Environment for Early Modern Low Countries History - aims to turn a comprehensive survey course in Early Modern Low Countries history into an educational online resource. * Reassembling the Thera Frescoes - assists archaeologists and conservators by digitising excavated fragments of wall paintings which have been preserved in volcanic ash since the sixteenth century BCE. * Mapping Sitelines - studies how rapid map authoring can support recovery after brain injury. * TEI by Example - is developing an online resource for teaching TEI ([[Text Encoding Initiative]]). * The Bentham Project is preparing a new definitive edition of The Collected Works of [[Jeremy Bentham]], the utilitarian philosopher, jurist, economist, political theorist and social reformer. * Transcribe Bentham - an effort to aid the transcription of [[Jeremy Bentham]]'s work by allowing volunteers to contribute.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Crowdsourcing Project Hopes to Make Short Work of Transcribing Bentham | work = The Chronicle of Higher Education|first = Travis | last = Kaya |accessdate = 2010-09-14| date = 2010-09-13 | url = http://chronicle.com/blogPost/Crowdsourcing-Project-Hopes-to/26829/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| last = Cohen| first = Patricia| title = For Bentham and Others, Scholars Enlist Public to Transcribe Papers| work = New York Times| location = New York| accessdate = 2011-04-09| date = 2010-12-27| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/28/books/28transcribe.html?_r=1&pagewanted=all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Leader: Members-only code is outdated|work=Times Higher Education|date=15 July 2010|accessdate=12 April 2012| first=Ann|last= Mroz|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=412539}}</ref> * The E Curator project - explores the use of 3D colour scanning and e-Science technologies to capture and share very large 3D colour scans and detailed datasets about museum artefacts in a secure computing environment.
